import { push } from builtins;

// `char[]` is str-shaped (see `is_char_array` in aipl-codegen); str has no
// in-place-growable form, so the first push onto a char array that started
// as an untyped empty literal (`mut cs = []`) must convert its
// representation. That conversion can only safely happen once, but the
// compiler can't prove a given push call site runs only once (e.g. inside a
// loop, the same compiled code runs every iteration) — so it's rejected
// rather than risking silent corruption on a second run. Starting from a
// real `char[]` literal (`mut cs = ['a']`) avoids the issue entirely — see
// `push_char.aipl`.
fn main() {
    mut cs = [];
    cs.push('a');
}
--- errors ---
error: cannot push a char onto an array that started as an untyped empty literal (`mut cs = []`) — initialize it with a char first, e.g. "mut cs = ['a']", since the first push can't be proven to run only once
  --> input:14:5
   |
14 |     cs.push('a');
